One America, Two Kinds of Citizens
New York — As I write this article, officials across the United States are still counting ballots from the 2020 presidential election.
Once the final statistical results are confirmed, recounts and legal challenges are certainly to follow.
This was expected in this fiercely competitive election, which saw a record voter turnout.
Only U.S. citizens can vote in the presidential election, but this choice affects people all over the country.
If it is too early to determine the election results now, it is certainly not too early to explore the implications of this election for the world's most powerful country.
On the positive side, the United States remains a powerful democratic country.
Despite the practical limitations related to the pandemic, voter turnout remained high.
This process seems to be proceeding according to plan.
Moreover, violent incidents are rare.
The court is investigating a decision by the U.S. Postal Service that appears to have been made for political motives and hindered the delivery of ballots from areas expected to predominantly vote Democratic.
Late Tuesday evening, the current U.S. president, Trump, made an unsubstantiated claim of victory that received almost no response, while his demand to stop the vote counting—particularly in the states where he was leading—seemed to be completely ignored.
However, it is concerning that the divisions among American voters remain significant.
The votes for the two candidates are almost equal.
It is no surprise that this division is likely to lead to a divided government.
If the current trend continues, the Democratic Party will win the White House and maintain control of the House of Representatives, while the Republican Party will continue to control the Senate.
The seats in the governor's office and the state legislature are almost evenly split between the two parties, with Republicans having a slight edge.
The anticipated "blue wave" for the Democratic Party did not materialize.
Biden is likely to win the popular vote by a significant margin, possibly securing around four to five million votes out of nearly 160 million total votes.
But Republicans held onto many Senate seats that many had predicted would flip, while Democrats actually lost seats in the House.
This result does not stem from a strong mandate, nor does it arise from political compromise.
Trump's polling numbers are very strong, with him receiving 5 million more votes than in 2016, making him the second-highest vote-getting presidential candidate in U.S. history and surpassing any previous winner.
Notably, this occurs against the backdrop of record-high daily increases in both new COVID-19 cases—over 100,000—and deaths—over 1,000.
Just as the consequences of his government's mishandling of the epidemic became most severe, nearly half of the voters turned to support him.
Even if Trump loses, which seems likely, he will still hold significant influence, especially if he continues to remain in the public eye, which also seems possible.
Even if he does not run for office himself, he is likely to have a significant influence on the selection of the Republican nominee in the next presidential election in 2024.
The Republican Party will be far removed from the party of Presidents Bush or Reagan.
Trumpism — a modern form of American populism — will still remain a powerful force.
Not surprisingly, despite having no evidence to back it up, Trump made every effort to portray himself as noble and upright, attempted to undermine the legitimacy of the election results, and accused the existence of election fraud.
Many of his supporters will reject the legitimacy of Biden serving as president.
Trump is very likely to never concede, and even less likely to attend the swearing-in ceremony of his successor.
As Will Rogers once said, Trump has never met a rule he couldn't break.
Americans are increasingly living in different worlds.
They categorize themselves into different communities and regions based on shared viewpoints.
And each world tends to watch its own cable television channels, listen to its own radio stations and podcasts, and visit its own websites.
The absence of a national civic curriculum provides convenience for the differentiation among people of different generations.
It is worth emphasizing that in most cases, the division of the nation is not along economic lines.
People from all social classes voted for the two candidates, and the voting patterns by demographics, gender, and race were not as one-sided as many had predicted.
Their disagreement mainly lies in the remedial measures.
Educational level is clearly an indicator of political orientation, as is geographical location. Republican voters are more likely to live in suburban and rural areas, while Democratic voters tend to reside in metropolitan regions.
However, the role of culture in American politics may be greater than any other factor.
In fact, foreign policy does not seem to be a major issue in the campaign, except when it comes to mobilizing specific constituencies, such as the large Cuban and Venezuelan communities in South Florida.
Against such a backdrop, it is difficult to gain public support for major reforms in the way the president is elected or how the government operates.
This situation is no different from the reform of the United Nations Security Council.
Many people believe that the current system has serious flaws and lacks representativeness. However, it is impossible to reach a consensus on reforms, because any potential solution would benefit some people while harming others.
It is no surprise that those who will suffer losses due to change will resist it.
This will make governance difficult.
This will largely depend on Mitch McConnell, the Republican leader in the Senate, and his ability and willingness to cooperate with President Biden going forward.
Collaboration also requires Biden to make compromises, which will certainly face resistance from the more ideologically rigid members of his party.
Democrats have tried to sharply reject everything Trump and his representatives stand for.
But they were not successful.
Meanwhile, Republicans are seeking an election that would validate Trump.
But this did not go as they had hoped.
On the contrary, the election reveals a nation and two types of citizens.
They will have to coexist; but whether they can do so remains to be seen.
